			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> paper:</span><br><i>Integrating Model Checking into a Live Modeling Environment</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JoeriExelmans.html">Joeri Exelmans</a>, <a href="../profile/CiprianTeodorov.html">Ciprian Teodorov</a>, <a href="../profile/HansVangheluwe.html">Hans Vangheluwe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742718">10.1145/3732771.3742718</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagM">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Model checking is a formal-methods technique, and integrating it is the paper’s primary contribution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The setting is live modeling where models execute under an interpreter and are edited at runtime.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4e.html"><span class="tagL">T4E: Simulation</span></a><ul><li> Witness traces/counterexamples are produced as integrated execution scenarios, aligning with simulation-style exploration of behaviours.
</li></ul></li></ul>
